The association between prehospital HMGB1 and sepsis in emergency care

Stuthi Iyer

25 April 2022

knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.retina = 2.5)
knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.align = "center", message=F, warning=F)

#Load Libraries
library(bookdown)
library(gridExtra)
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(table1)

#Load Data
my_data1 <- read_excel("~/Downloads/Reduced Data Set 2.xlsx")
# Calculating validated clinical illness risk score
my_data1$agescore <- ifelse (my_data1$Care_Age >= 45, 0, 1)
if (my_data1$RespRate<12){
  my_data1$RRscore <- 1
}
if (my_data1$RespRate>12 && my_data1$RespRate<=23){
  my_data1$RRscore <- 0
}
if (my_data1$RespRate>23 && my_data1$RespRate<=35){
  my_data1$RRscore <- 1
}
if (my_data1$RespRate>=36){
  my_data1$RRscore <- 2
}
my_data1$SBPscore <- ifelse (my_data1$SBP <= 90, 1, 0)
my_data1$HRscore <- ifelse (my_data1$HeartRate >= 120, 1, 0)
my_data1$POscore <- ifelse (my_data1$PulseOximetry >= 88, 0, 1)

my_data1$CIRScore <- my_data1$agescore+my_data1$RRscore+my_data1$SBPscore+my_data1$HRscore+my_data1$POscore
# Merging Pairs of Data for Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Tests
my_data2 <- data.frame(my_data1$Pair, my_data1$`Experimental Paradigm`, my_data1$Care_Age, my_data1$care_sex, my_data1$elix, my_data1$care_race, my_data1$RespRate, my_data1$SBP, my_data1$PulseOximetry, my_data1$HeartRate, my_data1$CIRScore, my_data1$`hHMGB1 (ng/mL)`, my_data1$ems_lactate_val, my_data1$il6_ems, my_data1$il10_ems, my_data1$tnf_ems, my_data1$Hosp_los, my_data1$ICU, my_data1$Dead)

my_data_case <- my_data2[which(my_data2$my_data1..Experimental.Paradigm.=="Case"),]
my_data_control <- my_data2[which(my_data2$my_data1..Experimental.Paradigm.=="Control"),]

# Fixing names of categories
colnames(my_data_case) <- c("Pair","Experimental Paradigm","Age", "Sex", "Elix", "Race", "RespRate", "SBP", "PulseOx", "HeartRate", "CIRS", "HMGB1", "Lactate", "IL6", "IL10", "TNF", "HospLOS", "ICU", "Dead")
colnames(my_data_case) <- paste(colnames(my_data_case),"case",sep="_")
colnames(my_data_case)[1] <- "Pair"

colnames(my_data_control) <- c("Pair","Experimental Paradigm","Age", "Sex", "Elix", "Race", "RespRate", "SBP", "PulseOx", "HeartRate", "CIRS", "HMGB1", "Lactate", "IL6", "IL10", "TNF", "HospLOS", "ICU", "Dead")
colnames(my_data_control) <- paste(colnames(my_data_control),"control",sep="_")
colnames(my_data_control)[1] <- "Pair"

my_data_final <- merge(my_data_case,my_data_control,by="Pair")

1 Background

More than 750,000 Americans are hospitalized with sepsis annually, and one in five patients may not survive. Emergency medical services (EMS) provide essential care for more than half of hospitalized sepsis patients, yet the diagnosis of sepsis may be delayed or missed. However, the prehospital interval is a key opportunity for early sepsis recognition, initiation of treatment, and emergency department (ED) notification. Prior prehospital studies developed sepsis recognition models based on subjective data and vital signs with limited success.

Plasma biomarkers provide key information about the presence of acute infection and organ dysfunction in other acute care settings, yet are understudied during prehospital care. One important sepsis biomarker is high mobility group box protein 1 (HMGB1), a ubiquitously expressed nuclear tolerance protein of the damage-associated molecular pattern (DAMP) family. HMGB1 is passively and actively released into circulation as part of early inflammatory response, where it activates innate immune cells. By binding to cell surface receptors, HMGB1 activates endothelial cells, further increasing production of pro-inflammatory cytokines and chemokines. Higher concentrations of HMGB1 are associated with mortality in sepsis, and modulation of HMGB1-mediated responses has been shown to reduce mortality in animal models.

2 Methods

This study prospectively determined the association between prehospital circulating HMGB1 and sepsis among non-trauma, non-arrest patients transported to a hospital. An individually matched case-control cohort of subjects was drawn from the Pittsburgh Prehospital LINking Evaluation (PIPeLINE) study (NIH GM104022) that enrolled adult (age 18 years) non-trauma, non-arrest prehospital patients at risk for sepsis who were transported by the City of Pittsburgh Bureau of EMS between August 2013 and February 2014 (N=345). We randomly selected 20 cases using Sepsis-3 criteria within 24 hours of admission and individually matched with 20 nearest neighbor non-septic controls on the following characteristics: i.) sex, ii.) age, iii.) race, and iv.) Elixhauser comorbidity index. This project was approved by the Human Research Protection Office of the University of Pittsburgh (STUDY19070378).

EMS clinical data were gathered for each patient encounter from a computerized medical record database (emsCharts, Inc; Warrendale, PA), and linked to electronic health record data at UPMC hospitals (Cerner Powerchart; Cerner, Kansas City, MO). Prehospital vital signs were used to calculate a validated clinical risk score. From the inpatient record, length of stay, rates of intensive care unit (ICU) admission, and in-hospital mortality were determined.

Prehospital blood samples were collected by EMS at the time of prehospital peripheral IV catheter placement and processed by the research team upon ED arrival, as described elsewhere. Plasma samples were frozen at -80C until assay. Samples were batch analyzed after a single freeze-thaw cycle for interleukin-6 (IL-6), interleukin-10 (IL-10), and tumor necrosis factor (TNF). Plasma levels of HMGB1 were quantified using an HMGB1 express enzyme linked immunosorbent assay (Tecan; Cat. No.30164033). Blood processing and analysis were completed by the Clinical Research, Investigation, and Systems Modeling of Acute Illness (CRISMA) Clinical Research Biospecimen Core. Demographic and clinical characteristics of patients with and without Sepsis-3 were described. Comparisons between groups were completed with Wilcoxon signed-rank tests for continuous data and Fishers exact tests for categorical data. We considered outlier values as two standard deviations above the mean, log transformed HMGB1 values, and reported results as significant at a two-sided p-value of 0.05. R statistical software version 4.1.2 (R Core Team, Vienna, Austria) was employed for statistical analysis.

Description of HMGB1 Concentrations by Treatment Group: Distributions are depicted by the side-by-side boxplots and histograms. The case group of patients with sepsis-3 in 24 hours has over double the median HMGB1 concentration at 6.5, which correlates with its release upon infection and damage to cells, and is especially clear from the table. The IQRs are 4.3 for the case group and 4.4 for the controls, showing that the middle 50% of data values has similar overall spread. The cases show a relatively normal distribution while the controls show a right-skew. Though different, the minimum values still fall within the bounds of the boxplot/histogram. It is worth noting that the minimum value for the case group was extrapolated due to one of two replicates being below the lower limit of detection (0 ng/mL); otherwise, each reported value is an average of the duplicate values. There is also an additional extrapolated value in this group following the same procedure.

3.1.1 Hypothesis Testing Procedure

H0: The population median difference in HMGB1 for cases and controls is equal to zero. H1: The population median difference in HMGB1 for cases and controls is not equal to zero.

The Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test is used specifically for comparisons of matched pairs and when there are doubts about having normal distributions.

The conditions of this test are that we have simple random samples of our overall patient set and that we have symmetric distributions of our populations of differences, which we will take to be true. That said, we can now run our Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test.

wilcox.test(my_data_final$HMGB1_case, my_data_final$HMGB1_control, paired=TRUE, correct=FALSE)

    Wilcoxon signed rank exact test

data:  my_data_final$HMGB1_case and my_data_final$HMGB1_control
V = 173, p-value = 0.0007896
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

We return a p-value of 0.0007896 at a 0.05 significance level from this statistical software. This means that if the null hypothesis were true, the probability that we would observe our test statistic, W = 271.5, or a value more extreme is 0.0007896. Because our p-value is less than our significance level, we reject our null hypothesis that the population median HMGB1 concentrations for the case and control groups are equal.

We have evidence to suggest that the population median from the case group is not equal to the population median from the control group.
